==English==
===Etymology===
Adjective: Middle English from Latin ''retrogradus''
<br>Verb: Latin ''[[retrogradi]]'' or Late Latin ''[[retrogradare]]'' (''[[gradi]]'', "walk").

===Adjective===
{{en-ad|retrograde}}
# Directed backwards, retreating; reverting especially inferior state, declining; inverse, reverse; movement opposite to normal or intended [[motion]], often circular motion.
# [[counterproductive|Counterproductive]] to a [[desire]]d [[outcome]].
===Noun===
{{en-noun|retrograde|retrogrades}}
# A [[degenerate]] person.
===Verb===
{{en-verb|retrograde|retrogrades|retrograded|retrograding}}
#{{intransitive}} To [[move]] [[backwards]]; to [[recede]]; to [[retire]]; to [[decline]]; to [[revert]].
*{{intransitive}} (''Astronomy'') To show [[retrogradation]].

